# ae3d13ea896848179c6a4268177de2d5
#: ../../admin-guide/transparent-proxy/wccp-configuration.en.rst:2
msgid "WCCP Configuration"
msgstr ""

# f65aa4e0b45444b3b0e5552ec7a79a2f
#: ../../admin-guide/transparent-proxy/wccp-configuration.en.rst:26
msgid ""
"`WCCP "
"<http://cio.cisco.com/en/US/docs/ios/12_0t/12_0t3/feature/guide/wccp.html>`_"
" is de-facto semi-standard used by routers to redirect network traffic to"
" caches. It is available on most Cisco™ routers although it does not "
"appear to be officially supported by Cisco. The primary benefits of WCCP "
"are"
msgstr ""

# b24172c9494e4ac99e37eb2076027e06
#: ../../admin-guide/transparent-proxy/wccp-configuration.en.rst:32
msgid ""
"If already have a router that supports WCCP inline you do not have to "
"change your network topology."
msgstr ""

# 3e87cf62eb704aaca5a0510ca89fcd9d
#: ../../admin-guide/transparent-proxy/wccp-configuration.en.rst:34
msgid ""
"WCCP fails open so that if the Traffic Server machine fails, it is "
"bypassed and users continue to have Internet access."
msgstr ""

# eb63b267e5354fc0888eaa057ba403a6
#: ../../admin-guide/transparent-proxy/wccp-configuration.en.rst:37
msgid ""
"Use of WCCP only makes sense for client side transparency [1]_ because if"
" the clients are explicitly proxied by Traffic Server there's no benefit "
"to WCCP fail open, as the clients will continue to directly access the "
"unresponsive Traffic Server host. It would be better to adjust the "
"routing tables on the router for explicit proxying."
msgstr ""

# a6e31bb719cc411cb3a40a0d035ee6f0
#: ../../admin-guide/transparent-proxy/wccp-configuration.en.rst:43
msgid ""
"Because the router serves as the inline network element, Traffic Server "
"must run on a separate host. This host can be located anywhere as long as"
" Traffic Server is either on the same network segment or a GRE tunnel can"
" be maintained between the Traffic Server host and the router."
msgstr ""

# 72aba8938cfc46b6862767b4184ed89b
#: ../../admin-guide/transparent-proxy/wccp-configuration.en.rst:48
msgid ""
"|important| This document presumes that the router is already properly "
"configured to handle traffic between the clients and the origin servers. "
"If you are not certain, verify it before attempting to configure Traffic "
"Server with WCCP. This is also a good state to which to revert should the"
" configuration go badly."
msgstr ""

# c7987fe323e14e01b89f50671953acb7
#: ../../admin-guide/transparent-proxy/wccp-configuration.en.rst:55
msgid "Configuration overview"
msgstr ""

# 995db5d455624d31aca4fce2f3e5251c
#: ../../admin-guide/transparent-proxy/wccp-configuration.en.rst:57
msgid ""
"Setting WCCP is a three step process, first configuring the router, the "
"Traffic Server host, and Traffic Server."
msgstr ""

# 31a9685fac1d4836b8be6817e07c990d
#: ../../admin-guide/transparent-proxy/wccp-configuration.en.rst:60
msgid ""
"|image1| The router will **not** respond to WCCP protocol packets unless "
"explicitly configured to do so. Via WCCP, the router can be made to "
"perform packet interception and redirection needed by Traffic Server "
"transparency. The WCCP protocol in effect acts as means of controlling a "
"rough form of policy routing with positive heartbeat cutoff."
msgstr ""

# dea3beec8fd84b738b1f1cd7f69425a9
#: ../../admin-guide/transparent-proxy/wccp-configuration.en.rst:66
msgid ""
"The Traffic Server host system must also be configured using ``iptables``"
" to accept connections on foreign addresses. This is done roughly the "
"same way as the standard transparency use."
msgstr ""

# 3845d7dcc4e44018b8746d1b810096f4
#: ../../admin-guide/transparent-proxy/wccp-configuration.en.rst:70
msgid ""
"Finally Traffic Server itself must be configured for transparency and use"
" of WCCP. The former is again very similar to the standard use, while "
"WCCP configuration is specific to WCCP and uses a separate configuration "
"file, referred to by the :file:`records.config` file."
msgstr ""

# 9377ad56aac4415b8eb62af19bfd55f8
#: ../../admin-guide/transparent-proxy/wccp-configuration.en.rst:75
msgid ""
"The primary concern for configuration in which of three basic topologies "
"are to be used."
msgstr ""

# c8c2f6f651f24f488ab94f40c50895f9
#: ../../admin-guide/transparent-proxy/wccp-configuration.en.rst:78
msgid ""
"Dedicated -- Traffic Server traffic goes over an interface that is not "
"used for client nor origin server traffic."
msgstr ""

# 8e9f34cb14e743268aebcc13124d5f9b
#: ../../admin-guide/transparent-proxy/wccp-configuration.en.rst:80
msgid ""
"Shared -- Traffic Server traffic shares an interface with client or "
"server traffic."
msgstr ""

# 1fc8dfaed7a54e4b8a3958657a38d505
#: ../../admin-guide/transparent-proxy/wccp-configuration.en.rst:82
msgid "Inside Shared -- Traffic Server and client traffic share an interface."
msgstr ""

# e9843edc136c429491d61ca6546f493e
#: ../../admin-guide/transparent-proxy/wccp-configuration.en.rst:84
msgid ""
"Outside Shared -- Traffic Server and origin server traffic share an "
"interface."
msgstr ""

# 1fcf3242d3d74cb5843b1690dce32bf6
#: ../../admin-guide/transparent-proxy/wccp-configuration.en.rst:87
msgid ""
"In general the dedicated topology is preferred. However, if the router "
"has only two interfaces one of the shared topologies will be required "
"[2]_ Click the links above for more detailed configuration information on"
" a specific topology."
msgstr ""

# af83562a746e4788a56c7ce60070f22f
#: ../../admin-guide/transparent-proxy/wccp-configuration.en.rst:93
msgid "Shared interface issues"
msgstr ""

# 06eecb554bb6424498dc3d8392e0395c
#: ../../admin-guide/transparent-proxy/wccp-configuration.en.rst:95
msgid ""
"A shared interface topology has additional issues compared to a dedicated"
" topology that must be handled. Such a topology is required if the router"
" has only two interfaces, and because of these additional issues it is "
"normally only used in such cases, although nothing prevents it use even "
"if the router has three or more interfaces."
msgstr ""

# 475b7525af674188a9d079940bf6dc3c
#: ../../admin-guide/transparent-proxy/wccp-configuration.en.rst:101
msgid ""
"The basic concept for a shared interface is to use a tunnel to simulate "
"the dedicated interface case. This enables the packets to be "
"distinguished at layer 3. For this reason, layer 2 redirection cannot be "
"used because the WCCP configuration cannot distinguish between packets "
"returning from the origin server and packets returning from Traffic "
"Server as they are distinguished only by layer 2 addressing [3]_. "
"Fortunately the GRE tunnel used for packet forwarding and return can be "
"used as the simulated interface for Traffic Server."
msgstr ""

# 890e194941a642dfa49c347638e62ad1
#: ../../admin-guide/transparent-proxy/wccp-configuration.en.rst:111
msgid "Frequently encountered problems"
msgstr ""

# 3288977e4eb54f8c903e944e80ae7ff0
#: ../../admin-guide/transparent-proxy/wccp-configuration.en.rst:114
msgid "MTU and fragmentation"
msgstr ""

# 5fcd72de1bdb478c82bd41b4d135b360
#: ../../admin-guide/transparent-proxy/wccp-configuration.en.rst:116
msgid ""
"In most cases the basic configuration using a tunnel in any topology can "
"fail due to issues with fragmentation. The socket logic is unable to know"
" that its packets will eventually be put in to a tunnel which will by its"
" nature have a smaller `MTU "
"<http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Maximum_transmission_unit>`_ than the "
"physical interface which it uses. This can lead to pathological behavior "
"or outright failure as the packets sent are just a little too big. It is "
"not possible to solve easily by changing the MTU on the physical "
"interface because the tunnel interface uses that to compute its own MTU."
msgstr ""

